p://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/video/2012/jun/27/queen-martin-mcguinness-video\">Queen shook hands with Sinn Féin&apos;s Martin McGuinness</a>.</p> <p>The historic encounter between the former IRA commander - now Northern Ireland&apos;s deputy first minister - and the Queen was unthinkable a little over 10 years ago.</p> <p>But the success of the peace process and the Queen&apos;s acclaimed visit to the Republic of Ireland last year, when her conciliatory words and gestures won over many critics of the monarchy, paved the way for their meeting.</p> <p>The much-anticipated first handshake took place away from the media spotlight behind closed doors.</p> <p>They later shook hands in public. McGuinness held the monarch&apos;s hands for a few moments and spoke to her in Irish. He told her the words meant: &quot;Goodbye and God&apos;s speed.&quot;</p> <p>McGuinness was a senior member of the IRA when it killed the Queen&apos;s cousin Lord Mountbatten in a bomb blast in 1979.</p> <p>The Queen is the head of Britain&apos;s armed forces, seen in the past by Republicans as occupying troops in Northern Ireland.</p> <p>The pair met in a room within Belfast&apos;s Lyric theatre during an event celebrating the arts in the Republic and Northern Ireland.<br /> <br />In a quiet space used by the Lyric for creative learning, the two were joined by the Duke of Edinburgh, the Northern Ireland first minister, Peter Robinson, the Irish president, Michael D Higgins, and his wife, Sabina.</p> <p>The McGrath Suite – named in honour of benefactor Harvey McGrath, former chairman of British insurer Prudential, and his wife, Allison – is usually filled with toddlers enjoying storytelling sessions or drama students taking part in workshops.</p> <p>But on Wednesday it was sparsely furnished with leather seating – four chairs and a sofa – set around a circular wooden table decorated with flowers, with tea, coffee and still and sparkling water on a side table.</p> <p>The floor-to-ceiling windows looking out on to landscaped gardens and the river Lagan were covered with curtains.</p>","wordcount":"323","commentable":"false","creationDate":"2012-06-27T10:35:03Z","internalComposerCode":"56ac5c3ae4b0c42dd192f4e8","internalOctopusCode":"1765580","internalPageCode":"1765580","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2012-06-27T14:28:07Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-06-27T00:00:00Z","productionOffice":"UK","publication":"theguardian.com","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/38tzn","shouldHideAdverts":"false","showInRelatedContent":"true","legallySensitive":"false","lang":"en","internalRevision":"1","internalShortId":"/p/38tzn"},"apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/uk/2012/jun/27/queen-martin-mcguinness-shake-hands","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/jun/27/queen-martin-mcguinness-shake-hands","webTitle":"Queen and Martin McGuinness shake hands and make history","webPublicationDate":"2012-06-27T10:41:00Z","sectionName":"UK news","sectionId":"uk-news","type":"article","id":"uk/2012/jun/27/queen-martin-mcguinness-shake-hands","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"section":{"id":"uk-news","webTitle":"UK news","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/uk-news","editions":[{"id":"uk-news","webTitle":"UK news","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/uk-news","code":"default"}]},"isHosted":false},"packages":[{"packageId":"7375d955-e5e6-11e5-8b19-4b0968a5a8b5","articles":[{"metadata":{"id":"internal-code/page/1765973","articleType":"article","group":"included"},"content":{"references":[],"elements":[{"id":"gu-image-392276208","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2012/6/27/1340818066275/Peter-Robinson-and-deputy-008.jpg","typeData":{"altText":"Peter Robinson and deputy first minister Martin McGuinness wait to meet Queen Elizabeth in Belfast","caption":"Queen Elizabet